    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-07T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-07T06:00:00-05:00" n="1088"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1088">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.11B114A/11–744: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-07T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >November 7, 1944—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received November 7—9
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7377. American Interests—Philippines—Prisoners of War Assistance. Department’s
                    3383, September 30, midnight.<note n="28" xml:id="d1088fn28">Not printed.</note>
                    Foreign Office note November 2 referring to the Department’s 2860, August 18
                        [<hi rend="italic">19</hi>], and Legation’s 6068, September 14,<note n="29"
                        xml:id="d1088fn29">Latter not printed; but for summary, see footnote 93,
                            <ref target="#pg_1049">p. 1049</ref>.</note> states Swiss Legation,
                    Tokyo, reports it authorized forward 180,000 pesos to prisoner of war camps
                    Philippines. Necessary permit for future payments must be obtained each month
                    from Japanese Ministries of War and Finance. Relief will be distributed 20 pesos
                    monthly per person and will be utilized best possible by Japanese camp
                    commanders but latter will be informed of Department’s desire that relief
                    preferable be used communal purchases medicines and food. Pertinent Japanese
                    regulations prescribed receipts must be signed by Japanese camp commander but
                    men of confidence exceptionally permitted sign them.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
